<br>
So much has been said in the past two days that anything I have to add seems almost redundant. But the one point I would still like to make is this: I think the terrorists' actions have backfired in some unanticipated ways.<br>
<br>
After the attack, in a matter of minutes, the people of this country became more galvanized than at any time since World War II. Partisan bickering dissolved in seconds. In New York, stores and restaurants threw open their doors to rescue workers. Strangers carried one another to safety -- or died trying. Blood banks instantly had donors lined up around the block. Amazon.com alone raised over three million dollars in 48 hours. In Australia, American Embassies are being overwhelmed with flowers. Buckingham Palace played the Star Spangled Banner during the Changing of the Guard. I heard one tale of a guy in Italy who had strangers walk up and hug him on the street when they found out he was American.<br>
<br>
Indeed, many of the very people the terrorists thought would celebrate their actions are instead appalled beyond words.<br>
<br>
America, to put it bluntly, is a basically a collective badass. The kind of country that, even when some ass-weasel sneaks up and clobbers her from behind with a lead pipe, stands back up. Spits out a bloody tooth. Rolls up her sleeves and shows everybody what she's made of.<br>
<br>
Our sleeves are rolled up, now, and I think what we are made of will prove nothing short of breathtaking.<br>
<br>
- Holley Irvine, Editor, Site Design/Maintenance <br>
